records.full_caption: Figure 1. Tensile elastic modulus at room temperature vs the Tg of p(g42T-T) from ref 12 (blue open circle), of conjugated polymers with alkyl side chains from refs 22−27 (blue filled symbols) and refs 28, 29 (blue half-filled symbols); tensile elastic modulus estimated using E = 2G(1 + ν), where G is the shear elastic modulus and assuming a Poisson ratio of ν = 0.5) as well as the value measured in this study for p(g42T-T) (pink open diamond), which increases by at least two orders of magnitude (red arrow) upon the addition of 11 or 20 vol % CNF (pink filled diamonds).

Figure 3. Tensile deformation of dry nanocomposites. (a) Engineering stress vs strain recorded at room temperature by tensile deformation of neat p(g,2T-T) (blue) and p(g,2T-T):CNF nanocomposites (red). The inset shows the stress−strain curves for neat and 3 vol % CNF nanocomposites. (b) Young’s modulus of p(g,2T-T):CNF nanocomposites as a function of the volume percentage (vol %) of CNF. The dashed and solid lines are predictions made using the Halpin-Tsai and Ouali models, respectively. The data points and error bars represent the mean value and min−max error for measurements of three to four individual samples.
records.caption: Young’s modulus of p(g,2T-T):CNF nanocomposites as a function of the volume percentage (vol %) of CNF. The dashed and solid lines are predictions made using the Halpin-Tsai and Ouali models, respectively. The data points and error bars represent the mean value and min−max error for measurements of three to four individual samples.

records.full_caption: Figure 5. (a) Representative AFM images of neat p(g2,7-T) (top) and a nanocomposite film containing 20 vol % CNF (bottom) when dry (left) and swollen, measured while submerged in deionized water (right). records.full_caption: Figure 4. Water uptake. (a) Schematic of the swelling experiments. (b) Young’s moduli of p(g2,7-T):CNF nanocomposites as a function of vol % CNF for initial vacuum-dried samples (blue squares), samples swollen in deionized water (blue circles), and the same samples dried again in vacuum (red triangles). Each data point and error bar represent the mean value and min−max error for measurements of two to four individual samples.
records.caption: Young’s moduli of p(g2,7-T):CNF nanocomposites as a function of vol % CNF for initial vacuum-dried samples (blue squares), samples swollen in deionized water (blue circles), and the same samples dried again in vacuum (red triangles). Each data point and error bar represent the mean value and min−max error for measurements of two to four individual samples.

records.full_caption: Figure 7. OECTs. (a) Dimension-normalized source−drain current IDS/(W × d/L) (left) and corresponding transconductance gm = gds/(W × d/L) (right, VDS = −0.7 V, VGS = +0.5 to −0.7 V), where W, d, and L are the width, thickness, and length of the channel. (b) Trajectory of μ and C* values upon varying VGS from +0.1 to −0.6 V; VDS = −0.1 V. (c) Maximum volumetric capacitance Cmax and (d) hole mobility μmax as a function of the CNF concentration (see Table 1 for the description of errors).
records.caption: Hole mobility μmax as a function of the CNF concentration (see Table 1 for the description of errors).

records.full_caption: Figure 6. (a) Schematic of planar devices and measurement setup used to extract the mobility of Cl− ions μCl− (R.E., reference electrode; C.E., counter electrode; and W.E., working electrode). (b) Representative optical images of the channel of devices comprising p(g2,2T-T) (top) and a nanocomposite comprising 20 vol % CNF (bottom) before applying a potential and after applying a potential of V = 1 V for 60 s at the working electrode. The gray scale depicts the relative intensity ΔI = I0 − I normalized by the initial intensity I0. (c) μCl− as a function of the CNF concentration (mean values and minimum error of two measurements) for an aqueous electrolyte (100 mM NaCl).
records.caption: μCl− as a function of the CNF concentration (mean values and minimum error of two measurements) for an aqueous electrolyte (100 mM NaCl).

records.full_caption: Figure 7. Transient analysis of OECT devices. (a) Representative plot of the IDS response (triangles: data, dashed lines: exponential fits using eqs 9 and 10) upon application of voltage steps at the gate electrode (left: VGS = 0 to −0.6 V; right: VGS = 0 to 0 V). (b) Plot of the time constants τon (upper triangles) and τoff (lower triangles) vs IDS as well as linear fits (solid lines) for devices based on p(g2T-TT) (blue) and nanocomposites comprising 20 % CNF (red).
